{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"11e7b900-810c-4694-84d0-de5c322ecf7c","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these places:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates `.ips` or `.crash` files:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for the same files with symbolicated stack traces.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — Disabled by default. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file typically appears in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **`log show`** — Check the unified log for crash context:\n   ```bash\n   log show --predicate 'eventMessage contains \"your_app_name\"' --last 1h\n   ```\n\n**Tip:** The `.ips` crash report is usually the fastest path — it's generated automatically and contains the faulting thread, signal info, and stack trace without any prior setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fbe01a1f-1a13-4ef6-9a94-c95e96e5f287","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET application on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":312,"requestId":"9819:187D22:73A8B04:8064E75:69F40646"},"id":"77c11ed6-72ef-40e7-b691-21ab8cd5a968","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:47:58.885Z","parentId":"f2d987a6-7844-4c99-90f9-0b9ad4a80ce8"}
